onary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Scarisbrick (Lancs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Scaresbrook","meanings":["English:  see  Scarisbrick  ."]},{"name":"Scaysbrook","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Scarisbrick  ."]},{"name":"Scarsbrook","meanings":["English:  see  Scarisbrick  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fitz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Fitz Henry De Scarisbrick was born on 18 August 1123, in Lathom House, Lancashire, England. He had at least 1 son with Emma de Grelle. He died on 2 December 1185, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"18 August 1123–2 December 1185":"18. august 1123–2. detsember 1185","1152–1172":"1152–1172","1170–1238":"1170–1238","1123–1185":"1123–1185","1238":"1238","1172 aged 15 - 24":"1172","1123":"1123","2 December 1185":"2. detsember 1185","1185":"1185","1152":"1152","18 August 1123":"18. august 1123","1172":"1172","1170":"1170","Lathom House, Lancashire, England":"Lathom House, Lancashire, England","Scarisbrick, West Lancashire, Lancashire, England":"West Lancashire, Lancashire, England","Dalton, Lancashire, England":"Dalton, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"18 August 1123–2 December 1185":"18. elokuuta 1123–2. joulukuuta 1185","1152–1172":"1152–1172","1170–1238":"1170–1238","1123–1185":"1123–1185","1238":"1238","1172 aged 15 - 24":"1172","1123":"1123","2 December 1185":"2. joulukuuta 1185","1185":"1185","1152":"1152","18 August 1123":"18. elokuuta 1123","1172":"1172","1170":"1170","Lathom House, Lancashire, England":"Lathom House, Lancashire, England","Scarisbrick, West Lancashire, Lancashire, England":"West Lancashire, Lancashire, England","Dalton, Lancashire, England":"Dalton, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"18 A